/*
DIRECTOR'S BONEYARD — Development intention:
The scene is about the weight of a ordinary kindness
extended to someone whose other life you didn't know.
Mary didn't protect a criminal.
She protected the version of him she knew.
Those are two different moral acts.
The scene must hold both without resolving either.
*/

# THE WITNESS
## Level 3 — Oscar / World-Class

= Synopsis: Detective Harris questions Mary Chen, who protected a regular customer
= she knew only as a man who came in every Thursday and said thank you like he meant it.
= The scene is about what we owe each other inside the smaller world we make.

FADE IN:

INT. LENA'S ALL-NIGHT — 3:17 A.M.

> "Somewhere between night and morning" <

The diner holds the hour the way old stone holds cold — completely, and from the inside. Fluorescent light the color of no mercy. Coffee that crossed into philosophy sometime around two. A jukebox that's been unplugged since Clinton and that people still put quarters into, the way we reach for things that used to work.

MARY CHEN (48, has absorbed enough of other people's troubles to have built a second skeleton from them) stands at the end of the counter with a glass and a cloth. The glass is already clean. The polishing is not about the glass.

*The yellow police tape across the street is visible through the window. Mary's back is to it. She knows exactly where it is.*

DETECTIVE FRANK HARRIS (54, carries his twenty-six years like a second coat — doesn't slow him down, doesn't keep him warm) pushes through the door. He does not move like urgency. Urgency closes doors. He sits at the counter.

He puts nothing on it. No notebook. No badge folio. No recorder. Just his hands — palms down, fingers loose — the body language of: *I'm not here to take anything.*

HARRIS
(as opening as an opener gets)
You make the pie yourself?

MARY
My mother's recipe.

HARRIS
Good baker?

MARY
She's been gone seven years.

*Harris takes that in the way it deserves to be taken in. A full beat. Not a performance of sympathy. The real thing.*

HARRIS
I'm sorry.

MARY
(not dismissing it — accepting it)
It was a good seven years of pie since.

She pours coffee he didn't ask for. He wraps both hands around the mug. The warmth is real and he lets it be. Outside, one police cruiser. No one in it.

*Neither of them looks at the window.*

HARRIS
You were on when it happened.

MARY
I'm on when everything happens.
Night shift is the everything shift.

HARRIS
The man who left running. Black leather.

MARY
(the length of a decision in a half-beat)
He left in a hurry.

HARRIS
He left in a hurry and he didn't pay
and you didn't call it in. And when
Brennan came in, you said you'd seen
nothing unusual.

The glass on the counter stops moving. Mary's hands go still the way a room goes still before weather.

HARRIS (CONT'D)
(not accusation — something worse, something adjacent to mercy)
How long was he a regular?

*The fluorescents hum one sustained note. The jukebox holds its decades of silence. The cook in the back has turned off the radio.*

MARY
(and when she speaks, she is testifying to something the law has no category for)
His order was medium roast, two sugars.
He came in every Thursday night after ten.
Four years. He always sat at that stool.

*She doesn't look at the stool. She's already looked at it too many times tonight.*

MARY (CONT'D)
He tipped exactly twenty percent —
I think he calculated it on his phone —
and he always said thank you like
it was a complete sentence.

She sets the cloth on the counter with the deliberateness of someone setting down something heavier.

MARY (CONT'D)
(the moral weight of the whole scene
in the space between these two lines)
I didn't know what he did
outside of here.

A breath. A long one.

HARRIS
But you knew who he was.

MARY
(the distinction she has been building
toward since before he walked in the door)
I knew who he was
in here.

*Harris looks at his coffee. Drinks it slowly. Sets it down. The way he does it says: I am not going to make this harder. I know what it costs. I'm not adding to the bill.*

HARRIS
I'll need a formal statement.
Photographs. Make it official.

MARY
I know.

HARRIS
(standing, and because it's true)
The pie any good?

MARY
(what passes for a smile in this hour)
It's the best thing I make.

He leaves money on the counter. Enough for the coffee three times over. He goes.

*Mary stands in the fluorescent mercy of 3:17 in the morning.*

She picks up the mug Harris left behind. Looks at it. Sets it down at the stool where four years of Thursdays used to sit.

She fills it fresh. The steam rises in the still air.

The coffee waits on the counter, hot and untouched, for someone who isn't coming back.

*The jukebox. The unplugged jukebox. Holds its silence.*

FADE TO BLACK.

===

# APPENDIX: LEVEL 3 CRAFT REFERENCE

= Every element in this scene is load-bearing. Nothing decorative.

## Specificity

= "3:17 A.M." — not 3 A.M. The extra seventeen minutes are a real world.
= "Medium roast, two sugars. Every Thursday after ten. Four years." — a relationship
= built in eleven words. The grief is proportional because the specificity earns it.
= "Twenty percent. Calculated it on his phone." — behavior as character biography.
= "Said thank you like it was a complete sentence." — this is the whole moral
= architecture of the scene in eight words.

## Physicality as Psychology

= Harris puts nothing on the counter — the body language of not taking.
= Neither character looks at the window where the tape is — complicity as staging.
= The glass stops moving when the questioning sharpens — hands as emotional tell.
= "Sets the cloth down with the deliberateness of someone setting down something heavier."
= The DP does not need to be told what to shoot. The action line IS the shot.

## Dialogue Architecture

= "I knew who he was in here." — seven words carrying the entire moral
= question of the scene: what do we owe the person someone is
= inside the small world they share with us?
= Harris and Mary do not argue. They negotiate. The tension is the gap
= between what is known and what is sayable.
= Neither character is wrong. That is Level 3.

## Image as Final Statement

= The last image — fresh coffee steaming at an empty seat — is the scene's
= true last line. The writer knows when words are finished.
= A great cinematographer reads this and knows: wide shot, low angle on the stool,
= the steam catching the fluorescent light, Mary out of focus in the background.
= That frame contains everything the preceding pages built toward.

[[
THE SPECTRUM IN PRACTICE:

Level 1: The audience knows what happened.
Level 2: The audience feels the tension.
Level 3: The audience carries something home.

The craft distance from Level 1 to Level 3 is not vocabulary or technique.
It is specificity, earned by observation.
It is subtext, earned by trusting the reader.
It is the image that does the work the words no longer need to.

Every story can be written at every level.
The writer chooses which world the reader lives in
for the duration of the reading.
]]
